<DOC><DOCNO> AP880810-0274 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-08-10-88 1351EDT</FILEID><FIRST>a a AM-ReligionRdp Adv12   08-10 0578</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Religion Rdp, Adv 12,0602</SECOND><NOTE>$Adv12</NOTE><NOTE>For Release Fri AMs, Aug. 12, and Thereafter</NOTE><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   U.S. Jewish population rose slightly last yearto an estimated 5.9 million, representing 2.5 percent of thepopulation, reports the 1988 Jewish Yearbook.   Biggest gains were reported in the Sunbelt and West Coast areas,with a 50,000 increase in the San Francisco-Oakland-San Jose area,and 30,000 increase in Florida.   Of 15 states reporting a drop in Jewish population, New York,whose 1,891,400 make it No. 1 in Jewish population, had thegreatest absolute loss, down 20,000.   Biggest relative loss occurred in Mississippi, which fell from3,005 to 2,400 Jews.</TEXT><DATELINE>GARY, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Roman Catholic Bishop Norbert Gaughan hasprohibited use of church facilities in the diocese for partisanpolitical gathering, saying the church does not endorse any partyor candidate.   His action came after pro-life groups complained that candidateswho support legalized abortion were speaking at parish facilities.</TEXT><DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The Church of Jesus Chist of Latter-daySaints (Mormon) has reiterated its policy of strict politicalneutrality _ of not endorsing any candidates or parties and notusing church facilities for political purposes.   The church's first presidency added that it does urge ``allvoters to involve themselves in the political process.''</TEXT><DATELINE>CANTERBURY, England (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Anglican bishops have reversed acentury-old ban on baptizing polygamists in cultures where polygamyis socially established. The new policy upholds monogamy as theideal and forbids converted polygamists from taking any more wives.   The change was approved at the Anglican global LambethConference, which ended last weekend. Kenyan Bishop David Gitarisaid it has been inconsistent to extend pastoral care to divorcees,despite Jesus's strictures against divorce, yet not to tolerateAfrican polygamy, about which Jesus was silent.</TEXT><DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A group of influential Greek Orthodox lay peoplehas set up an independent lay organization, the Orthodox ChristianLaity, seeking to restore and strengthen the role of the laity inthe church.   Lay people have been ``neglected or relegated to mostlyfund-making roles'' of ``silent obedience'' apart from churchgovernance, the group said, adding that church history shows``laity and clergy are equal partners.''</TEXT><DATELINE>GLORIETA, N.M. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Churches are experiencing a worseningshortage of organists, says a Southern Baptist music specialist.   ``The problem is universal,'' Sharron Lyon told a meeting here.``All denominations have the same problem.''   She said few college students now major in organ. At a recentmeeting of the American Guild of Organists, she said, participantsquestioned whether musicians would be considering careers asorganists by the end of the century.</TEXT><DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The Evangelical Lutheran Church in America, whichbegan its life last Jan. 1 with merger of three former Lutheranbodies, had 5,272,984 members in 11,127 congregations at itsoutset, reports the church secretary, the Rev. Lowell Almen.</TEXT><DATELINE>DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The National Catholic Rural LifeConference has called on Christians across the country to join inprayer on Monday, Aug. 15, for mutual community support and droughtrelief.   ``The drought of 1988 has reminded us of our dependence uponwater, as well as our dependence upon our creator who gives us thatwater,'' said the national group's executive director, Joseph K.Fitzgerald.   ``In these difficult times, we remember that it is our relianceupon God and one another than enables us to get throughdifficulties.''</